# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kdb-q-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] Whitney studied pure mathematics at the graduate level at the University of Toronto in the early 1980s.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] He was first exposed to APL when he was 11 by its inventor, Ken Iverson, a family friend.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] He later worked extensively with APL, first at I.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] Sharp Associates alongside Ken Iverson and Roger Hui among others.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] Whitney is recognized as having had an "enduring and significant influence on APL" and he co-authored papers with both Ken Iverson and Roger Hui.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] He also wrote the initial prototype of J, a terse and macro-heavy single page of code, in one afternoon, which then served as the model for J implementor, Roger Hui, and was responsible for suggesting the rank operators in J.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] In 1988, Whitney began working at Morgan Stanley developing financial applications.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] At Morgan Stanley, Whitney developed A+ to facilitate migrating APL applications from IBM mainframe computers to a network of Sun Microsystems workstations.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] A+ had a smaller set of primitive functions and was designed for speed, and to handle large sets of time series data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] In 1993, Whitney left Morgan Stanley and co-founded Kx Systems with Janet Lustgarten, to commercialize his k programming language.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] According to Paul Ford's 2015 cover-story for *Businessweek*, k is a programming language that is "famous for its brevity." The company signed an exclusive agreement with Union Bank of Switzerland and Whitney developed a variety of trading applications using k until the contract expired.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] At the outset of the contract Whitney developed the kdb database built on k.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] In 2003, Kx Systems released q, a new vector language that built upon k and the kdb+ database developed by Whitney.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] In 2018, First Derivatives bought out Whitney and Lustgarten's minority shares of Kx Systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] Whitney and Lustgarten then founded Shakti.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] The Shakti platform has a small memory footprint, and allows for fast deployment and processing of distributed elastic workloads.
[src:kdb-q-lang/arthur-whitney-computer-scientist] It can work with all kinds of datasets, including numerical, temporal and text data, whether structured or not.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:kdb-q-lang/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The evolution of financial technology spans more than a century, marked by significant technological innovations that have reshaped the financial industry.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] While the application of technology to finance has deep historical roots, the term "financial technology" emerged in the late 20th century and gained prominence in the 1990s.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] However, the term didn't gain popularity until the early 1990s when Citicorp Chairman John Reed used it to describe the Financial Services Technology Consortium.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This project, initiated by Citigroup, was designed to promote technological cooperation in the financial sector, marking a pivotal moment in the industry's collaborative approach to innovation.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The financial technology ecosystem includes various types of companies.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] While startups developing new financial technologies or services are often associated with financial technology, the sector also encompasses established technology companies expanding into financial services and traditional financial institutions adopting new technologies.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This diverse landscape has led to innovations across multiple financial sectors, including banking, insurance, investment, and payment systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Financial technology applications span a wide range of financial services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] These include digital banking, mobile payments and digital wallets, peer-to-peer lending platforms, robo-advisors and algorithmic trading, insurtech, blockchain and cryptocurrency, regulatory technology, and crowdfunding platforms.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The evolution of financial technology often involves the crossover of telecommunications engineering into finance.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] There is growing empirical evidence that FinTech innovations — especially digital payment systems, mobile money and online financial platforms — significantly contribute to financial inclusion.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] A 2025 systematic review found that such technologies improve access to financial services in developing and underserved communities by reducing barriers to banking and enabling secure, affordable transactions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Despite overall positive effects on financial inclusion, digital financial services may exclude people with limited internet access, low digital or financial literary, or lower confidence using online services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] It also raises consumer-protection concerns around fraud, cybersecurity and data privacy.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The late 19th century laid the groundwork for early financial technology with the development of the telegraph and transatlantic cable systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] These innovations transformed the transmission of financial information across borders, enabling faster and more efficient communication between financial institutions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] A significant milestone in electronic money movement came with the establishment of the Fedwire Funds Service by the Federal Reserve Banks in 1918.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This early electronic funds transfer system used telegraph lines to facilitate secure transfers between member banks, marking one of the first instances of electronic money movement.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The 1950s ushered in a new era of consumer financial services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Diners Club International introduced the first universal credit card in 1950, a pivotal moment that would reshape consumer spending and credit.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This innovation paved the way for the launch of American Express cards in 1958 and the BankAmericard (later Visa) in 1959, further expanding the credit card industry.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The 1960s and 1970s marked the beginning of the shift from analog to digital finance, with several groundbreaking developments that shaped the future of financial technology.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] In 1967, Barclays introduced the world's first ATM in London, expanding access to cash and basic banking services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Inspired by vending machines, the ATM marked a significant step towards self-service banking.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Financial technology infrastructure continued to evolve with the establishment of the Inter-bank Computer Bureau in the UK in 1968.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This development laid the groundwork for the country's first automated clearing house system, eventually evolving into BACS (Bankers' Automated Clearing Services) to facilitate electronic funds transfers between banks.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The world of securities trading was transformed in 1971 with the establishment of NASDAQ, the world's first digital stock exchange.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] NASDAQ's electronic quotation system represented a significant leap forward from the traditional open outcry system used in stock exchanges.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Two years later, the founding of the SWIFT (Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication) standardized and secured communication between financial institutions globally.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] SWIFT's messaging system became the global standard for international money and security transfers.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The introduction of electronic fund transfer systems, such as the ACH (Automated Clearing House) in the United States, facilitated faster and more efficient money transfers.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The ACH network allowed for direct deposits, payroll payments, and electronic bill payments, significantly reducing the need for paper checks.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The 1980s and 1990s witnessed significant developments in financial technology, with the rise of digital financial services and the early stages of online banking.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] A major breakthrough came when Michael Bloomberg founded Innovative Market Systems (later Bloomberg L.P.) and introduced the Bloomberg Terminal.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This innovation transformed how financial professionals accessed and analyzed market data, providing real-time financial market data, analytics, and news to financial institutions worldwide.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Online banking emerged in the early 1980s, with the Bank of Scotland offering the first UK online banking service called Homelink.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This service allowed customers to view statements, transfer money, and pay bills using their televisions and telephones.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The late 1980s saw the development of EDI (Electronic Data Interchange) standards, allowing businesses to exchange financial documents electronically and streamlining B2B (business-to-business) transactions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] A significant milestone in consumer digital banking came in 1994 when Stanford Federal Credit Union launched the first Internet banking website.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This service initially allowed members to check account balances online, with bill pay functionality added in 1997.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] However, it was not until 1999 that the first state-chartered, FDIC-insured institution operating primarily online was established.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] First Internet Bank, founded by David Becker, marked a new era in online-only banking.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The late 1990s and early 2000s marked a significant turning point in the evolution of financial technology, as numerous innovations emerged during the dot-com boom.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] One notable development was the rise of online trading platforms, with E-Trade, founded in 1982, leading the charge.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] In 1992, E-Trade became one of the first financial services companies to offer online trading to consumers, revolutionizing the way individuals interacted with the stock market.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Another pivotal moment was the founding of PayPal in 1998.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] PayPal's success in creating a secure and user-friendly online payment system demonstrated the viability of digital payment solutions and paved the way for numerous subsequent financial technology startups.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The early 2000s also saw the emergence of innovative business models in the financial services industry.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] WebBank, established in 1997, began offering a "rent-a-charter" model in 2005, providing the necessary banking infrastructure and regulatory compliance for financial technology startups to offer banking services without obtaining their own charters.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This model would later prove crucial in enabling the growth of numerous financial technology companies.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The 2008 financial crisis served as a catalyst for the rapid growth of the financial technology industry, as declining trust in traditional financial institutions created opportunities for innovative, technology-driven solutions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The early days of the post-crisis era saw the emergence of digital currencies, with e-Gold serving as a precursor to the development of Bitcoin.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] While e-Gold, which allowed users to create accounts denominated in grams of gold and enable instant transfers, ultimately faced legal challenges and closure, it laid the foundation for future digital currencies.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The invention of Bitcoin in 2008 by an anonymous creator using the pseudonym Satoshi Nakamoto marked a turning point in the evolution of digital currencies and decentralized finance.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Bitcoin's use of blockchain technology sparked a wave of development in the field of cryptocurrencies, opening up new possibilities for secure, transparent, and decentralized financial systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] As the financial technology landscape continued to evolve, new payment processing companies entered the market, offering developer-friendly APIs that dramatically simplified online payment integration.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] By lowering the barriers to entry for e-commerce and online financial services, these companies played a crucial role in enabling the growth of new financial technology startups and driving innovation in the sector.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The partner banking model, which emerged in the early 2000s, gained significant traction in the post-crisis era.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This model expanded beyond its initial "rent-a-charter" concept, evolving into more comprehensive partnerships between traditional banks and financial technology companies.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] These collaborations allowed for rapid innovation and market entry, as financial technology leveraged the regulatory compliance and infrastructure of established banks while bringing their own technological expertise and customer-centric approaches.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This further accelerated the growth of the financial technology sector, enabling the proliferation of digital-first financial services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The maturation of this model paved the way for the rise of neobanks, which challenged traditional banking paradigms by offering fully digital experiences, redefining customer expectations in the banking sector.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The increasing adoption of smartphones drove the development of mobile-first financial technology solutions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Square's introduction of a mobile card reader in 2009 enabled small businesses to accept credit card payments using smartphones, democratizing access to payment processing and highlighting the transformative potential of mobile technology in the financial services industry.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The evolution of mobile payment systems continued with the launch of Google Wallet in 2011 and Apple Pay in 2014, which further popularized mobile payments and demonstrated the growing consumer demand for convenient, secure, and user-friendly payment solutions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This period also saw the rise of peer-to-peer (P2P) payment applications.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] These platforms revolutionized how individuals transfer money, enabling quick and easy transactions between users.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] By allowing fast, direct transfers through mobile devices, P2P payment apps significantly reduced the friction in personal financial transactions, making it simpler for people to split bills, share costs, or send money to friends and family.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The global COVID-19 pandemic, which began in early 2020, had a profound impact on the financial technology industry, accelerating the adoption of digital financial services and highlighting the importance of technology in ensuring the resilience and accessibility of financial systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] As lockdowns and social distancing measures forced businesses and consumers to rely more heavily on digital channels, financial technology solutions experienced a surge in demand.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Mobile-first financial technology applications saw unprecedented growth during this period.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Many trading platforms reported significant increases in new user accounts, with some seeing millions of new funded accounts added in the early months of the pandemic.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Similarly, payment and money transfer apps experienced substantial user growth, with some platforms more than doubling their monthly active users over a three-year period, indicating a massive shift towards digital financial services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The events of 2020 also exposed the limitations of traditional financial institutions in meeting the needs of consumers and businesses in times of crisis.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Financial technology companies, with their agile and technology-driven business models, were better positioned to respond to the challenges posed by the rapidly changing environment, offering innovative solutions for remote banking, contactless payments, and digital lending.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] During this period, venture capital valuations for financial technology companies soared, driven by low interest rates and a booming stock market.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The surge in financial technology investments was marked by significant capital inflows, leading to higher valuations and more frequent exits via IPOs and SPACs.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Several prominent financial technology companies achieved record-breaking valuations, further underscoring the sector's growth and investor confidence.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The shift towards digital financial services during this period also accelerated the adoption of blockchain technology and cryptocurrencies.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] As central banks around the world explored the possibility of issuing digital currencies, the interest in decentralized finance and non-fungible tokens grew, opening up new avenues for innovation in the financial technology sector.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The financial technology landscape in Africa is on the rise, with active companies reaching 1,263 in 2024, a significant increase from 1,049 in 2022 and 450 in 2020.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Nigeria leads the financial technology sector, accounting for 28% of all financial technology companies on the continent, and hosting eight of Africa's nine fintech unicorns.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] By early 2025, Nigeria was home to more than 430 fintech companies, a 70% increase year-on-year, with fintech accounting for 72% of the country's total equity funding.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] African fintech startups collectively raised over US$3 billion in disclosed funding in 2025, a 33% year-on-year increase, as the sector shifted from rapid scaling toward sustainable growth and profitability.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The United Arab Emirates has emerged as the leading fintech hub in the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] By 2025, the DIFC had grown to host over 1,500 fintech, artificial intelligence, and innovation firms, ranking ninth among global fintech hubs according to the Global Financial Centres Index, and first in the Middle East.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The 2020s marked a new phase in financial technology, defined by the mainstream adoption of artificial intelligence across financial services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Beginning in 2023, generative AI tools were adopted by banks, payment processors, and investment platforms to automate customer service, credit decision-making, fraud detection, and portfolio management.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The rapid integration of AI into financial infrastructure also drew regulatory attention.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The Federal Reserve's Spring 2026 Financial Stability Report found that 50% of market contacts identified AI as a potential systemic shock to financial markets, up from 9% the previous year, representing a more than fivefold increase in perceived AI-related systemic risk in twelve months.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The decade also saw significant fintech expansion in emerging markets.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] In Africa, active fintech companies reached 1,263 in 2024, up from 450 in 2020, with Nigeria accounting for 28% of all companies on the continent.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] In the GCC, regulatory sandboxes established by the Dubai Financial Services Authority and Abu Dhabi Global Market accelerated fintech licensing, enabling a new generation of digital investment platforms to reach retail investors across the region.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The financial technology industry includes a diverse range of financial services and technologies that can be categorized into several key areas.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Many companies operate across multiple areas or create new niches that blur these distinctions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Financial technology companies utilize various revenue models, often combining multiple approaches to diversify income streams.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Transaction fees form a primary source of income for many financial technology businesses, particularly payment processors and cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] These companies typically charge a percentage of each processed transaction.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Some companies have expanded this model to include premium fees for services like instant payouts, catering to merchants who require immediate access to funds.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Interchange fees represent another significant revenue stream, particularly for firms offering payment cards.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Subscription and freemium models allow companies to offer basic services at no cost while charging for advanced features or premium tiers.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] This approach is common among digital banks and financial management platforms.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] In the business-to-business (B2B) sector, usage-based pricing is prevalent, especially for API services.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Financial technology infrastructure providers often charge based on the volume of API calls or transactions processed, enabling other businesses to access specialized financial services without developing them internally.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Interest-based revenue is crucial for many financial technology companies, particularly in the banking and lending sectors.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Digital banks and investment platforms typically earn interest on customer deposits and cash balances.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Lending platforms often combine interest revenue with loan sales, selling portions of their loan portfolios to other institutions or investors.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Data-driven revenue models, while potentially lucrative, have faced increasing scrutiny and regulation.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Some firms engage in data monetization, selling aggregated or anonymized user data to third parties.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] However, this practice has raised privacy concerns and regulatory challenges.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] A less controversial approach involves leveraging user data for targeted advertising and lead generation, earning revenue through product recommendations and referral fees while providing free services to users.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Some revenue models, such as payment for order flow (PFOF) used by certain brokerage firms, occupy a regulatory gray area.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] While PFOF allows for commission-free trades, potentially benefiting retail investors, it has faced scrutiny due to concerns about conflicts of interest and best execution practices.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Modern financial technology depends on a shared layer of technical infrastructure that enables applications, banks, and third-party providers to exchange data and initiate transactions securely.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Central to this infrastructure are standardised application programming interfaces (APIs), which allow software systems to communicate with one another without exposing underlying code or data directly.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Open banking represents the most significant regulatory formalisation of this API infrastructure to date.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Under open banking frameworks, banks are required to expose customer account data and payment services to authorised third parties via standardised APIs, subject to explicit customer consent.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] The model was first mandated at scale by the European Union's revised Payment Services Directive (PSD2) in 2018 and the UK's Open Banking Standard, established following a 2016 Competition and Markets Authority ruling.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Comparable frameworks have since been adopted globally, including the Financial Data Exchange (FDX) standard in the United States and the Consumer Data Right (CDR) in Australia, though these differ in terminology, technical standards, and implementation model.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] By 2024, the global open banking market was valued at approximately $31.6 billion and is projected to reach $135 billion by 2030.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] As financial technology companies seek to disrupt traditional financial services, some have been criticized for prioritizing growth over compliance, security, and consumer protection.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] In a notable controversy, cryptocurrency exchange FTX collapsed in November 2022, facing accusations of deceptive practices, improper handling of client assets, and insufficient risk controls.
[src:kdb-q-lang/financial-technology] Sam Bankman-Fried, FTX's founder and CEO, was later convicted of wire fraud, conspiracy, and money laundering.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:kdb-q-lang/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] kdb+ is a high-performance column-store database that was designed to process and store large amounts of data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] Commonly accessed data is pushed into random-access memory (RAM), which is faster to access than data in disk storage.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] Created with financial institutions in mind, the database was developed as a central repository to store time series data that supports real-time analysis of billions of records. kdb+ has the ability to analyze data over time and responds to queries similar to Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] Columnar databases return answers to some queries in a more efficient way than row-based database management systems. kdb+ dictionaries, tables and nanosecond time stamps are native data types and are used to store time series data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] At the core of kdb+ is the built-in programming language, q, a concise, expressive query array language, and dialect of the language APL.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In 1998, KX released kdb, a database built on the language K written by Arthur Whitney.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In 2003, kdb+ was released as a 64-bit version of kdb.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In 2004, the kdb+ tick market database framework was released along with kdb+ taq, a loader for the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) taq data. kdb+ was created by Arthur Whitney, building on his prior work with array languages.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In April 2007, KX announced that it was releasing a version of kdb+ for Mac OS X.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] Then, kdb+ was also available on the operating systems Linux, Windows, and Solaris.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In September 2012, version 3.0 was released.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] It was optimized for Intel's upgraded processors with support for WebSockets, and universally unique identifiers (UUIDs, termed *globally* unique identifiers (GUID)s in Microsoft software).
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] Intel's Advanced Vector Extensions (AVX) and Streaming SIMD Extensions 4 (SSE4) 4.2 on the Sandy Bridge processors of the time allowed for enhanced support of the kdb+ system.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In June 2013, version 3.1 was released, with benchmarks up to 8 times faster than older versions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] In March 2020, version 4.0 was released.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kdb] New features included multithreaded primitives, Intel Optane DC persistent memory support, and data at rest encryption.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] It was founded in 1993 by Janet Lustgarten and Arthur Whitney, the developer of the K programming language.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In 2014, First Derivatives increased their ownership interest to 65 percent; in 2018, the company (now FD Technologies plc) announced plans to buy out the remaining shares of KX.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] KX has offices in New York City, London, England, Ireland, Germany, Australia, Singapore, Tokyo, and Hong Kong.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In 1993, Whitney and Lustgarten joined to commercialize the k programming platform Whitney had created after building the A+ language and other trading systems at Morgan Stanley.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] The purpose of the software was to access and explore large data volumes in financial services computer systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] Initially, Kx Systems had an exclusive contract with Swiss global financial services firm UBS to provide them with the K language.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In 1998, the contract with UBS expired and the firm launched the kdb+ database.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] As part of kdb+, Whitney developed a new language named q that operated with k and uses English keywords.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In 1999, the company reached a marketing agreement with a Northern Ireland based firm, First Derivatives.; it opened an office in Manhattan in 2002, Germany and Japan in 2003, and Hong Kong in 2009.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In 2014, First Derivatives purchased a 65 percent share of Kx Systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] Kx became a technology supplier to NASA's Frontier Development Lab.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In July 2018, FD Technologies bought all remaining shares in KX Systems that it did not already hold; Whitney and Lustgarten then went on to found Shakti.
[src:kdb-q-lang/kx-systems] In 2025, FD Technologies sold KX to TA Associates as part of their downsizing of spinning-off divisions such as the company and other subsidiary First Derivative which was sold to EPAM Systems.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quants typically specialize in areas such as derivative structuring and pricing, risk management, portfolio management, and other finance-related activities.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The role is analogous to that of specialists in industrial mathematics working in non-financial industries.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative analysis often involves examining large datasets to identify patterns, such as correlations among liquid assets or price dynamics, including strategies based on trend following or mean reversion.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Applied quantitative analysis is commonly associated with quantitative investment management which includes a variety of methods such as statistical arbitrage, algorithmic trading, and electronic trading.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Some of the larger investment managers using quantitative analysis include Renaissance Technologies, Citadel Securities, D.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative finance started in 1900 with Louis Bachelier's doctoral thesis "Theory of Speculation", which provided a model to price options under a normal distribution.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Jules Regnault had posited already in 1863 that stock prices can be modelled as a random walk, suggesting "in a more literary form, the conceptual setting for the application of probability to stockmarket operations".
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] It was, however, only in the years 1960-1970 that the "merit of [these] was recognized" as options pricing theory was developed.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Harry Markowitz's 1952 doctoral thesis "Portfolio Selection" and its published version was one of the first efforts in economics journals to formally adapt mathematical concepts to finance (mathematics was until then confined to specialized economics journals).
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Markowitz formalized a notion of mean return and covariances for common stocks which allowed him to quantify the concept of "diversification" in a market.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] He showed how to compute the mean return and variance for a given portfolio and argued that investors should hold only those portfolios whose variance is minimal among all portfolios with a given mean return.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Thus, although the language of finance now involves Itô calculus, management of risk in a quantifiable manner underlies much of the modern theory.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Modern quantitative investment management was first introduced from the research of Edward Thorp, a mathematics professor at New Mexico State University (1961–1965) and University of California, Irvine (1965–1977).
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Considered the "Father of Quantitative Investing", Thorp sought to predict and simulate blackjack, a card-game he played in Las Vegas casinos.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] He was able to create a system, known broadly as card counting, which used probability theory and statistical analysis to successfully win blackjack games.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] His research was subsequently used during the 1980s and 1990s by investment management firms seeking to generate systematic and consistent returns in the U.S. stock market.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The field has grown to incorporate numerous approaches and techniques; see Outline of finance § Quantitative investing, Post-modern portfolio theory, Financial economics § Portfolio theory.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] In 1965, Paul Samuelson introduced stochastic calculus into the study of finance.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] In 1969, Robert Merton promoted continuous stochastic calculus and continuous-time processes.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Merton was motivated by the desire to understand how prices are set in financial markets, which is the classical economics question of "equilibrium", and in later papers he used the machinery of stochastic calculus to begin investigation of this issue.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] At the same time as Merton's work and with Merton's assistance, Fischer Black and Myron Scholes developed the Black–Scholes model, which was awarded the 1997 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] It provided a solution for a practical problem, that of finding a fair price for a European call option, i.e., the right to buy one share of a given stock at a specified price and time.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Such options are frequently purchased by investors as a risk-hedging device.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The various short-rate models (beginning with Vasicek in 1977), and the more general HJM Framework (1987), relatedly allowed for an extension to fixed income and interest rate derivatives.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Similarly, and in parallel, models were developed for various other underpinnings and applications, including credit derivatives, exotic derivatives, real options, and employee stock options.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quants are thus involved in pricing and hedging a wide range of securities – asset-backed, government, and corporate – additional to classic derivatives; see contingent claim analysis.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Emanuel Derman's 2004 book *My Life as a Quant* helped to both make the role of a quantitative analyst better known outside of finance, and to popularize the abbreviation "quant" for a quantitative analyst.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] In sales and trading, quantitative analysts work to determine prices, manage risk, and identify profitable opportunities.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Historically this was a distinct activity from trading but the boundary between a desk quantitative analyst and a quantitative trader is increasingly blurred, and it is now difficult to enter trading as a profession without at least some quantitative analysis education.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Front office work favours a higher speed to quality ratio, with a greater emphasis on solutions to specific problems than detailed modeling.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] FOQs typically are significantly better paid than those in back office, risk, and model validation.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Although highly skilled analysts, FOQs frequently lack software engineering experience or formal training, and bound by time constraints and business pressures, tactical solutions are often adopted.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Increasingly, quants are attached to specific desks.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Two cases are: XVA specialists, responsible for managing counterparty risk as well as (minimizing) the capital requirements under Basel III; and structurers, tasked with the design and manufacture of client specific solutions.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative analysis is used extensively by asset managers.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Some, such as FQ, AQR or Barclays, rely almost exclusively on quantitative strategies while others, such as PIMCO, BlackRock or Citadel use a mix of quantitative and fundamental methods.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] One of the first quantitative investment funds to launch was based in Santa Fe, New Mexico and began trading in 1991 under the name Prediction Company.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] By the late-1990s, Prediction Company began using statistical arbitrage to secure investment returns, along with three other funds at the time, Renaissance Technologies and D.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Prediction hired scientists and computer programmers from the neighboring Los Alamos National Laboratory to create sophisticated statistical models using "industrial-strength computers" in order to "[build] the Supercollider of Finance".
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Machine learning models are now capable of identifying complex patterns in financial market data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] With the aid of artificial intelligence, investors are increasingly turning to deep learning techniques to forecast and analyze trends in stock and foreign exchange markets.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] See Applications of artificial intelligence § Trading and investment.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Major firms invest large sums in an attempt to produce standard methods of evaluating prices and risk.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] These differ from front office tools in that Excel is very rare, with most development being in C++, though Java, C# and Python are sometimes used in non-performance critical tasks.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] LQs spend more time modeling ensuring the analytics are both efficient and correct, though there is tension between LQs and FOQs on the validity of their results.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] LQs are required to understand techniques such as Monte Carlo methods and finite difference methods, as well as the nature of the products being modeled.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Often the highest paid form of Quant, ATQs make use of methods taken from signal processing, game theory, gambling Kelly criterion, market microstructure, econometrics, and time series analysis.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] This area has grown in importance in recent years, as the credit crisis exposed holes in the mechanisms used to ensure that positions were correctly hedged; see FRTB, Tail risk § Role of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Model validation (MV) takes the models and methods developed by front office, library, and modeling quantitative analysts and determines their validity and correctness; see model risk.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The MV group might well be seen as a superset of the quantitative operations in a financial institution, since it must deal with new and advanced models and trading techniques from across the firm.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Post crisis, regulators now typically talk directly to the quants in the middle office - such as the model validators - and since profits highly depend on the regulatory infrastructure, model validation has gained in weight and importance with respect to the quants in the front office.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Before the crisis however, the pay structure in all firms was such that MV groups struggle to attract and retain adequate staff, often with talented quantitative analysts leaving at the first opportunity.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] This gravely impacted corporate ability to manage model risk, or to ensure that the positions being held were correctly valued.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] An MV quantitative analyst would typically earn a fraction of quantitative analysts in other groups with similar length of experience.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] In the years following the crisis, as mentioned, this has changed.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative developers, sometimes called quantitative software engineers, or quantitative engineers, are computer specialists that assist, implement and maintain the quantitative models.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] They tend to be highly specialised language technicians that bridge the gap between software engineers and quantitative analysts.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The term is also sometimes used outside the finance industry to refer to those working at the intersection of software engineering and quantitative research.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The nonergodicity of financial markets and the time dependence of returns are central issues in modern approaches to quantitative trading.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Financial markets are complex systems in which traditional assumptions, such as independence and normal distribution of returns, are frequently challenged by empirical evidence.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Thus, under the non-ergodicity hypothesis, the future returns about an investment strategy, which operates on a non-stationary system, depend on the ability of the algorithm itself to predict the future evolutions to which the system is subject.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] As discussed by Ole Peters in 2011, ergodicity is a crucial element in understanding economic dynamics, especially in non-stationary contexts.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Identifying and developing methodologies to estimate this ability represents one of the main challenges of modern quantitative trading.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] In this perspective, it becomes fundamental to shift the focus from the result of individual financial operations to the individual evolutions of the system.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Operationally, this implies that clusters of trades oriented in the same direction offer little value in evaluating the strategy.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] On the contrary, sequences of trades with alternating buy and sell are much more significant.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Since they indicate that the strategy is actually predicting a statistically significant number of evolutions of the system.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Because of their backgrounds, quantitative analysts draw from various forms of mathematics: statistics and probability, calculus centered around partial differential equations, linear algebra, discrete mathematics, and econometrics.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Some on the buy side may use machine learning.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The majority of quantitative analysts have received little formal education in mainstream economics, and often apply a mindset drawn from the physical sciences.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quants use mathematical skills learned from diverse fields such as computer science, physics and engineering.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] These skills include (but are not limited to) advanced statistics, linear algebra and partial differential equations as well as solutions to these based upon numerical analysis.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] A typical problem for a mathematically oriented quantitative analyst would be to develop a model for pricing, hedging, and risk-managing a complex derivative product.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] These quantitative analysts tend to rely more on numerical analysis than statistics and econometrics.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] One of the principal mathematical tools of quantitative finance is stochastic calculus.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] A typical problem for a statistically oriented quantitative analyst would be to develop a model for deciding which stocks are relatively expensive and which stocks are relatively cheap.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] The model might include a company's book value to price ratio, its trailing earnings to price ratio, and other accounting factors.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] An investment manager might implement this analysis by buying the underpriced stocks, selling the overpriced stocks, or both.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Statistically oriented quantitative analysts tend to have more of a reliance on statistics and econometrics, and less of a reliance on sophisticated numerical techniques and object-oriented programming.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] These quantitative analysts tend to be of the psychology that enjoys trying to find the best approach to modeling data, and can accept that there is no "right answer" until time has passed and we can retrospectively see how the model performed.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Both types of quantitative analysts demand a strong knowledge of sophisticated mathematics and computer programming proficiency.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative analysis has traditionally been a major source of employment for those with PhD degrees in a quantitative discipline, and analysts often come from mathematics, applied mathematics, physics or engineering backgrounds, learning finance "on the job".
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] At the same time, the demand for quantitative skills has led to the creation of specialized Masters and PhD courses in financial engineering, mathematical finance and computational finance (as well as in specific topics such as financial reinsurance).
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] In particular, the Master of Quantitative Finance, Master of Financial Mathematics, Master of Computational Finance and Master of Financial Engineering are becoming popular with students and with employers.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] This has, in parallel, led to a resurgence in demand for actuarial qualifications, as well as commercial certifications such as the CQF.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Similarly, the more general Master of Finance (and Master of Financial Economics) increasingly includes a significant technical component.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] Likewise, masters programs in operations research, computational statistics, applied mathematics and industrial engineering may offer a quantitative finance specialization.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] While a quantitative analyst has typically needed extensive skills in computer programming — commonly C, C++ and Java, and lately R, MATLAB, Mathematica, and Python — data science and machine learning analysis and methods are increasingly employed.
[src:kdb-q-lang/quantitative-analysis-finance] As such graduates of Master's in these areas are also hired as quants.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:kdb-q-lang/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
